Using the discrete compound interest formula with 4 compounds per year,
we know that

\begin{align*}\displaystyle \$12000=\$10000(1+0.12/4)^{4t},\end{align*}

where \emph{t} is the time in years required for the \$10 000 investment
to grow to \$12 000. We want to solve for \emph{t}. Dividing both sides
by \$10000,

\begin{align*}\displaystyle 1.2=(1+0.03)^{4t}.\end{align*}

Taking the logarithm of both sides and simplifying,

\begin{align*}\ln(1.2)= \ln\left(1.03^{4t}\right) = 4t \ln\left(1.03\right)\end{align*}

Hence, the investment will take

\begin{align*}t= \frac{\ln(1.2)}{4\ln(1.03)}\end{align*}

years to grow to \$12000.

''A calculator would tell you that \emph{t} is about 1.54 years.''
